1174:     /**
1175:      * Invoking this method makes all buffered records immediately available to send (even if <code>linger.ms</code> is
1176:      * greater than 0) and blocks on the completion of the requests associated with these records. The post-condition
1177:      * of <code>flush()</code> is that any previously sent record will have completed (e.g. <code>Future.isDone() == true</code>
1178:      * and callbacks passed to {@link #send(ProducerRecord,Callback)} have been called).
1179:      * A request is considered completed when it is successfully acknowledged
1180:      * according to the <code>acks</code> configuration you have specified or else it results in an error.
1181:      * <p>
1182:      * Other threads can continue sending records while one thread is blocked waiting for a flush call to complete,
1183:      * however no guarantee is made about the completion of records sent after the flush call begins.
1184:      * <p>
1185:      * This method can be useful when consuming from some input system and producing into Kafka. The <code>flush()</code> call
1186:      * gives a convenient way to ensure all previously sent messages have actually completed.
1187:      * <p>
1188:      * This example shows how to consume from one Kafka topic and produce to another Kafka topic:
1189:      * <pre>
1190:      * {@code
1191:      * for(ConsumerRecord<String, String> record: consumer.poll(100))
1192:      *     producer.send(new ProducerRecord("my-topic", record.key(), record.value());
1193:      * producer.flush();
1194:      * consumer.commitSync();
1195:      * }
1196:      * </pre>
1197:      *
1198:      * Note that the above example may drop records if the produce request fails. If we want to ensure that this does not occur
1199:      * we need to set <code>retries=&lt;large_number&gt;</code> in our config.
1200:      * </p>
1201:      * <p>
1202:      * Applications don't need to call this method for transactional producers, since the {@link #commitTransaction()} will
1203:      * flush all buffered records before performing the commit. This ensures that all the {@link #send(ProducerRecord)}
1204:      * calls made since the previous {@link #beginTransaction()} are completed before the commit.
1205:      * </p>
1206:      * <p>
1207:      * <b>Important:</b> This method must not be called from within the callback provided to
1208:      * {@link #send(ProducerRecord, Callback)}. Invoking <code>flush()</code> in this context will result in a
1209:      * {@link KafkaException} being thrown, as it will cause a deadlock.
1210:      * </p>
1211:      *
1212:      * @throws InterruptException If the thread is interrupted while blocked
1213:      * @throws KafkaException If the method is invoked inside a {@link #send(ProducerRecord, Callback)} callback
1214:      */
1215:     @Override
1216:     public void flush() {
1217:         if (Thread.currentThread() == this.ioThread) {
1218:             log.error("KafkaProducer.flush() invocation inside a callback is not permitted because it may lead to deadlock.");
1219:             throw new KafkaException("KafkaProducer.flush() invocation inside a callback is not permitted because it may lead to deadlock.");
1220:         }
1221: 
1222:         log.trace("Flushing accumulated records in producer.");
1223: 
1224:         long start = time.nanoseconds();
1225:         this.accumulator.beginFlush();
1226:         this.sender.wakeup();
1227:         try {
1228:             this.accumulator.awaitFlushCompletion();
1229:         } catch (InterruptedException e) {
1230:             throw new InterruptException("Flush interrupted.", e);
1231:         } finally {
1232:             producerMetrics.recordFlush(time.nanoseconds() - start);
1233:         }
